name: Renal - Blood flow/Autoregulation
question1: What is the blood flow to each aspect of the kidneys?   What is the anatomy of the kidney?
contents:
Gross Anatomy

  • There are normally two separate kidneys each with its own fibrous capsule.
  • They are located in a retroperitoneal location in the upper abdomen, one in each para-vertebral gutter adjacent to T12 to L3.
  • They are approximately 12cm long and weigh 150 grams each.
  • The right kidney is slightly lower than the left due to the presence of the liver in the right upper abdomen.
  • The upper part (upper pole) of each kidney is protected posteriorly by the 11th and 12th ribs


Reference [https://www.frca.co.uk/Documents/273%20Renal%20Physiology%20-%20Part%201.pdf]


HINT: REMEMBER THE RULE OF 5s

  • > 1/5 of cardiac output
  • 1.2 L/min, 20-25% of cardiac output
  • > 500 mL/min to each kidney
  • > 500 mL/min/100 g tissue to the cortex
  • > 1/5 of this (100 mL/min/100 g tissue) to the outer medulla
  • > 1/5 of that (20 mL/min/100 g tissue) to the inner medulla


  • The renal artery enters each kidney at the hilum and divides into several branches.
  • Anterior and posterior main branches of the renal artery --> Segmental (large end arteries)
  • (1) Interlobar arteries (enter renal tissue at border of cortex and medulla) give rise to Arcuate (run an arc like course between cortex/medulla)
  • (2) interlobular arteries that give rise to
  • (3) afferent arterioles, which supply the
  • (4) glomerular capillaries (site of filtration).
  • Glomerular capillaries drain into
  • (5) efferent arterioles, which are PORTAL VESSELS as they carry blood from one capillary network to another.
  • In the outer two-thirds of the cortex,
  • (6) peritublar capillaries surround the proximal and distal convoluted tubules and collecting tubules.
  • In the inner one-third of the cortex, the
  • (7) Vasa Recta surround the loops of Henle and collecting ducts.
  • Arcuate veins

question2: What are the functions of renal blood flow?
contents2:
• (1) Provision of glucose and O2 to meet the metabolic demands of renal tissue
  • (2) Removal of CO2 and other products of metabolism
  • (3) Maintenance of GFR
  • (4) Provision of O2 for active reabsorption of Na+
contents3:
• Autoregulation describes the ability to maintain a constant RBF over a wide range of mean pressures
  • keeping the FLOW constant
  • despite changes in PRESSURE


Autoregulation Mechanisms

  • 1) Myogenic
  • most widely accepted explanation brought about by a direct contractile response of the afferent arteriolar smooth muscle to stretch.
  • An increase in perfusion pressure results in smooth muscle contraction and an increase in the renal vascular resistance, so maintaining a constant blood flow
  • Other factors affecting flow
  • Renal sympathetic nerve stimulation results in vasoconstriction of afferent arterioles thereby reducing RBF
  • Renal prostaglandins PG attenuate sympathetic-induced vasoconstriction through vasodilation, thereby increasing RBF
  • Angiotensin 2 vasoconstrict's the efferent arterioles more than the afferent arterioles thus maintaining glomerular filtration rate (GFR)
  • Tubulo-glomerular feedback -
  • Mediators present in blood vessel walls help to regulate GFR by vasodilatation (nitric oxide, NO) or vasoconstriction (endothelin)


PGE2 dilates afferent arterioles to maintain flow

  • Can be measured using the Fick principle
  • = blood flow can be calculated if the following are known:
  • Amount of marker substance taken up by the organ per unit time
  • Concentration of marker in arterial supply
  • Concentration of marker in venous blood

PGE2 EP1 Gq Effects:

  • Respiratory: Bronchoconstriction,
  • GIT Increased contraction
  • Renal Renal vasodilation (afferent arterioles)

PGE2 EP2 Gs Effects:

  • Respiratory: Bronchodilatation,
  • Vascular: closure of ductus arteriosus
  • GIT : decreased contraction
  • Renal: vasodilatation (afferent arterioles)

PGE3 EP2 Gi Effects:

  • GIT : gastric mucous production, GIT contraction
  • Uterine contraction.
question4: How can renal blood flow be measured? What principle does it utilise?
contents4:
RBF can be calculated by plasma clearance of Para-AminoHippuric acid [PAH]

  • as a modification of the Fick Principle


Fick principle-

  • Flow to an organ is equal to the uptake/excretion of a substance by an organ per unit time divided by the arterio-venous concentration difference of that substance across that organ (L/min)


Plasma clearance:

  • the volume of plasma cleared of a substance per unit time (mL/min).
  • PAH, an organic acid is used because:
  • it has a high extraction ratio (it is almost completely removed by the kidneys) via filtration and secretion,
  • therefore its A-V concentration difference across the renal vascular bed is equal to the renal arteriolar concentration. (A[PAF] - V[PAF]) = A[PAF]
  • it is neither utilised nor excreted by any other organ, therefore is peripheral venous plasma concentration is identical to its renal arterial concentration.


If we think of the Fick equation as Flow or Output = Consumption or Uptake / [A-V difference]


  • Applying the Fick equation,
  • PAH UPTAKE by the kidney is given by the product of urine PAH concentration and urine flow.
  • The A-V concentration difference is substituted by peripheral venous plasma concentration as explained above.
  • This gives us the equation for clearance.
  • Clearance of PAH = Urine [PAH] x urine flow / plasma [PAH]


Clearance helps us calculate renal plasma flow (RPF), since it is plasma, and not blood which is filtered.

RBF can then be deduced from RPF if the haematocrit (Hct) is known, by the equation:

  • RBF = RPF/1-Hct.
contents5:
Renal Physiology

o How does the body maintain urine output

o Renal perfusion

o RAAS


  • Maintained by autoregulation when MAP between 80-160mmHg, via:
  • (1) Myogenic response:
  • stretch dependent VG-calcium channels open at high pressures = SM contraction
  • (2) Tubuloglomerular feedback:
  • afferent arterioles constricted in response to INCREASED luminal concentrations of Na+ in the macula densa of the DCT
  • Therefore, renal autoregulation minimises the impact of changes in BP on Na+ excretion
  • (Not impacted by SNS)

Maintained in dennervated kidney

  • Constant flow is maintained despite fluctuations in pressure via afferent dilation and efferent vasoconstriction
  • Adenosine causes decreased renal blood flow and GFR
